I have been very lucky to have the family that I have. We are Latin-American. I was raised in the U.S., but everyone here describes me as a Latino. To Latinos however, I was a "Gringo''. From my father's side, my grandfather was a black Latino, with green eyes, my grandmother was tanned. From my mother's side, there were some tan, but they are all mostly white in skin color. 

I went to visit my family from my father's side for the first time, we were throwing a party for one of our elders. There was a sea of black people on the dance floor, I was the only white Hispanic. I have never felt more welcomed. They didn't treat me or anyone who entered the family through marriage or adoption any differently (We are huge. From my father's side alone, I think we can field 2-3 football teams lol).

My family shaped my beliefs when it comes to racism. Opening ourselves and exposing others to our culture would go a long way. We have too many walls dividing us, and we seem to forget that regardless of those subcategories, we are all human.
